<DOC><DOCNO> AP891221-0231 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 0825EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-RiteAid     12-21 0280</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Rite Aid,0290</SECOND><HEAD>Judge Refuses to Dismiss Rite Aid Charges</HEAD><DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A judge has refused to dismiss charges that thepresident of Rite Aid Inc. tried to bribe an Ohio State PharmacyBoard member.   Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Judge Lillian J. Greene onWednesday set a tentative trial date of Jan. 15 for Martin L.Grass, who heads the nation's largest drug store chain.   Grass, 35, and his attorneys appeared in court Friday to askGreene to drop the charges.   Grass has denied government charges that he and Rite Aid, whichis based in Shiremanstown, Pa., were trying to put people on thepharmacy board who were sympathetic to the company's interests.   A secret Cuyahoga County grand jury unsealed on Aug. 1 accusedGrass and Rite Aid of offering a $33,000 bribe to pharmacy boardmember Melvin Wilczynski. Prosecutors said the money was to be inexchange for Wilczynski's stepping down from the board.   Rite Aid has said it paid Wilczynski $33,249 for a legal buyoutof his consulting contract with Lane Drug Co., a division ofPeoples Drug Stores Inc. Rite Aid acquired Peoples Drug in April.   The indictment charges Grass and Rite Aid with bribery andpossession of criminal tools. It alleges that Grass and the companyused an aircraft as the criminal tool last March and April.   Both charges are felonies. The maximum penalty for the briberycharge is a 10-year prison term and a $5,000 fine, and the chargeof possession of criminal tools is punishable by a maximum of fiveyears in prison and a $2,500 fine.   Rite Aid has 29,000 employees and more than 2,200 discount drugstores across the nation.</TEXT></DOC>